node.text:
Let’s clear up a big public accounting myth today, shall we? That myth: Coming out of college, it’s BIG 4 or BUST to have a good start to a career in public accounting.

While there is certainly a benefit to getting one of those big names on your resume, there is plenty of excellent experience to be had at regional or even smaller firms.

The key difference in experience between the Big 4 and the smaller firms is depth vs. breadth of experience.

I’ve personally never worked at a Big 4, but from the people I know who have, you get to go super deep on a specific area of the tax code—and get really good at that specific area. This can be valuable because there are “riches in the niches.”

When you work at a smaller firm, though, you get to see the entire process, from cleaning up a business owner’s messy set of books, then entering it into the business return and finally how it reflects actual tax dollars on their bottom line.

The reality is there is no better or worse, it just depends on what YOU want out of your career. But I’ve spoken with too many college kids who fear that if they don’t get a job at a Big 4 right out of the gate, that their career is over before it begins.

And that is simply not true.

Tag a friend who works in accounting! And let me know if you’d like to hear more career advice like this from me. :)

node.title: Big 4 or Bust when starting your career?

node.text:
Have you relocated your business or moved into a new place recently?

Make sure you do not miss out on any potential moving deductions!

While moving expenses to relocate as an employee are no longer deductible, relocating your business is.

This means the cost to move (or buy new) furniture, the movers you hire, and the transportation expenses to get there are all definitely a tax deduction.

So be sure to pick all those in your books and don’t miss out on that expense!

node.text:
Have you considered a price increase recently? If you are growing but have not raised prices in forever, it might be time to assess your own belief in your worth!

A price increase (even a small one) is one of the easiest ways to immediately increase profits.

Consider this: if you have 20% margins—meaning for every 10 dollars of revenue you keep 2 dollars of profit—then just a 4% price increase would have the SAME impact as increase revenue volume by 20%

Yet almost no one revisits their pricing as part of their annual planning.

What I have noticed is that this is often a direct reflection of the mindset and self-worth of the owner.

So first off: consider a price increase if your business is growing.

And second: if you are feeling internal resistance to that price increase, take a look at why.

You might need to reflect on increasing your own self worth.

When is the last time you raised prices? Let me know in the comments!

node.title: Pricing is a reflection of your self-worth

node.text:
Why did we up and move our family to Florida?

If you’ve been following along my stories, you know that a week ago we arrived in our new home state—we picked up everything in our old hometown of Roseville, CA and loaded it on a truck bound for Palm Beach County.

It was a big decision and we are so excited to be here.

With the new remote-first work environment in many businesses, a lot of people are considering moving right.

So what were our big reasons?

First, business reasons. There are so many business opportunities down here. It seems like everyone wants to move down here, and that means lots of commerce. And when you boat by all these epic waterfront houses, you realize how much opportunity there truly is.

Plus, I’m here a couple times a year for @tonyrobbins Business Mastery event. By living here, I get to sleep in my own bed and see my family during those events.

Second, state income taxes. You’ve heard me teach about strategies to lower taxes constantly. By moving to a ZERO income tax state, I am “drinking my own champagne” and giving myself a 10%+ pay raise in the form of state tax savings.

Third, more freedom! You have to have been living under a rock in the last year to not hear about how poorly CA has been managing its affairs. We are excited to be in a state that trusts adults to think for themselves.

Last and perhaps most exciting: being near the water! Not counting the state tax savings, we can be in a house that is 10-15 minutes from the ocean for the same price as our old home in CA that was 2.5 hours inland.

We love beach time, island tunes, and everything that goes with that lifestyle—so we decided to live congruently with it!

Are you considering a big move soon? If so, where and why? I want to hear from you!

Raise your hand if you felt this in your bones! 🙋‍♂️🙋‍♀️

Often when business owners first start to see success in their business, they forget to plan for the massive tax bill that is coming.

And if you don’t proactively get yourself in the right entity type you can get walloped even more with the dreaded Self-Employment Tax.

What exactly is Self-Employment Tax?

It is your portion of Social Security and Medicare as a self-employed individual. As a W-2 employee, you have your gross wage and then amounts withheld from your paycheck--this includes income taxes, as well as line items for Social Security and Medicare.

Those two items total about 7.5% of your paycheck.

Your employer then matches that and sends 15% to the IRS; this is what funds those programs.

When you're self-employed, however, there's no one to match the 7.5% and no one to withhold amounts from your pay. So you end up stuck with 15.3% on top of your income tax, on the net income of your business.

It can be mitigated by forming an S-Corporation, but just be aware if you're in business for the first time that you could get a surprise nasty bill at Tax Day.

If you need help deciding whether an S-Corp is right for you to save THOUSANDS EACH YEAR, send me a DM and we can get a free call scheduled.

It was an exhausting few days of packing, but after a long red eye flight we made it to Florida!

Fun first couple days on the water so far, and excited to start earning my income completely free of state taxes!

If you’re leaving a high income tax state for a low one, make sure you handle that transition properly…otherwise you could end up still paying the old state’s tax!

Can’t wait to share more of our new Florida life in the weeks and months to come. 😎🌴🌞🐠

Are you thinking about adding a second location to your business, or moving it entirely? If so, this post will save you thousands of dollars.

But before I dive in I just want to say: moving across the country ain’t for the faint of heart!

When the Tax Reform laws were passed, they eliminated moving expenses as a deduction on the 1040—but what many people don’t realize it that was moving expenses for a new JOB, not relocating your business.

Moving expenses to relocate a business are still fully deductible.

This means that all the travel costs associated with searching for the new location (flights, hotels, meals while visiting) are all still deductible.

Other deductible items include moving costs (if you have to hire movers to transport furniture, inventory, or other items), your mileage when you drive your vehicle to your new location, and any storage costs if you need to store your goods during the transition process.

Relocating a business or adding a second location can be expensive. Make sure to help ease the burden of this expense by capturing all available moving expense deductions.

If you know someone who is moving their business, be sure to tag them in the comments!

#moving #smallbusiness #taxes

Where are my patriots? 🙋‍♂️🇺🇸

I always love reading this section of a letter written from John Adams to his wife on July 3, 1776:

"I am apt to believe that it will be celebrated, by succeeding Generations, as the great anniversary Festival. It ought to be solemnized with Pomp and Parade, with Shews, Games, Sports, Guns, Bells, Bonfires and Illuminations from one End of this Continent to the other from this Time forward forever more."

Happy birthday a day early, America. 

Now more than ever, it is imperative that we honor how our freedom was won and appreciate how great this country truly is.

And I’ll continue doing my part to help empower and educate the backbone of these United States—the small business owner.

Have a great celebration everyone!

Do you need to have a credit card in your business’s name to pay for business expenses on credit?

The short is no! But make sure you don’t mix business and personal expenses on the same card!

If you mix them and pay for your personal expenses with the card you use for business, there could be some potential tax and legal consequences there.

Also, for that credit card in your personal name that you are using as your business card, make sure to pay off that card directly from the business account!

Do you use a business credit card or a card in your name for your business expenses?

Let me know in the comments and share this one in your stories for other entrepreneurs to see 🤑

#smallbusiness #entrepreneur #cpa #accountant

node.text:
When you buy a car for your business through financing, you might be thinking you simply deduct the payments as auto expense.

If so, read on because that’s not exactly how it works!

When you buy and finance a car, you take the full purchase price and put it on your books as a fixed asset, then you take DEPRECIATION expense based on the purchase price.

The only thing that gets deducted from your payment is the interest amount paid during the year.

Because of this, you get the same deduction on the vehicle whether you pay for the car in CASH or take a loan out for the full amount.

Beyond the payment, all your other expenses like repairs, fuel, insurance, and anything else would be deducted as you pay them—so make sure to pay for those from your business bank account or credit card!

Send this a business owner who just bought a car, or hit that save button for the next time you buy one for yourself 🚗😎

If you enjoy a good weekend getaway, but also want it to be deductible, make sure to watch this video!

I’m down here in Orange County for a few days and realized it’s been a while since I’ve taught this strategy.

To make your weekend trips tax deductible, you can utilize a great strategy known as “wrapping a weekend.”

The IRS states that if you travel for business and work both Friday AND the following Monday, then the Saturday and Sunday in between count as business days.

What that means for you is that your hotel and meals during that weekend are entirely deductible.

It used to mean that your activities would also be deductible, but since they eliminated the entertainment expense deduction those no longer can be taken.

Still, tax-deductible hotels and meals make for a nice little discount on that weekend getaway! Just remember to document your business activities on both Friday and Monday so you have proper records!

Are you traveling anywhere this weekend? The airports definitely seem to be getting busier lately! Let me know in the comments!

TIME TOGETHER ONE ON ONE MATTERS.

How often do you get away with your spouse to change up your daily routine and reconnect?

I’m far from a marriage expert, but I can tell you that getting away together is essential for my relationship with @yogastrong_erika.

And that means time without kids! Family trips are awesome and create amazing memories, but to me you need that one-on-one time to reconnect.

Whenever we go too long without time away, the sometimes monotonous routine of life creeps in and it can cause me to take my wife for granted.

And let’s face it—as amazing as raising little ones together is, it’s also a grind! Throw running a business on top of that and it really becomes a challenge.

By getting away together for several days in a row, making memories and experiencing new adventures, we get to reconnect and just be with each other.

And of course, let that chest hair fly free. 🦍

If you have a significant other: do you make time to get away together? And how often? I’d love to hear about it in the comments!
